"Peng C.H., Guiot J., Van Campo E.","Past and future carbon balance of European ecosystems from pollen data and climatic models simulations",1998,"Global and Planetary Change","18","3-4",,"189","200",,,10.1016/S0921-8181(98)00021-6,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0032171658&partnerID=40&md5=c78ad23c294648e8e36c0464f6cc6223","Lab. de Bot. Hist. and Palynologie, CNRS UA 1152, Fac. de St. Jerome, Case 451, 13397 Marseille Cedex 20, France; Laboratoire d' Ecologie Terrestre, UMR 5552 (CNRS-UPS) 13, Avenue du Colonel Roche-BP 4403, 31405 Toulouse Cedex 4, France; Ontario Forest Research Institute, 1235 Queen Street East, Sault Ste. Marie, Ont. P6A2E5, Canada","Peng, C.H., Lab. de Bot. Hist. and Palynologie, CNRS UA 1152, Fac. de St. Jerome, Case 451, 13397 Marseille Cedex 20, France, Ontario Forest Research Institute, 1235 Queen Street East, Sault Ste. Marie, Ont. P6A2E5, Canada; Guiot, J., Lab. de Bot. Hist. and Palynologie, CNRS UA 1152, Fac. de St. Jerome, Case 451, 13397 Marseille Cedex 20, France; Van Campo, E., Laboratoire d' Ecologie Terrestre, UMR 5552 (CNRS-UPS) 13, Avenue du Colonel Roche-BP 4403, 31405 Toulouse Cedex 4, France","As climate changes, there is considerable uncertainty whether nothem hemisphere ecosystems will act as atmospheric CO2 sinks or sources. Here, we used statistical models calibrated on field measurements, past terrestrial biomes and climates inferred from pollen and future climatic change scenarios simulated by General Circulation Models (GCMs), to investigate the processes controlling past, present and future CO2 fluxes in the European ecosystems. Our results suggest that climatic change can significantly affect spatial and temporal variations of net primary production and soil respiration, and alter the net ecosystem exchange of CO2. Most of the potential terrestrial biomes in Europe will likely change from a net CO2 sink, which provided a negative feedback for atmospheric CO2 during the last 13 000 yr BP, to a net CO2 source, providing a positive feedback following global warming. The results further illustrate that there is no analogue in the recent past (Late Quaternary) for the probable future ecosystem dynamics.","Carbon balance; Climatic model simulation; CO2 sink; CO2 source; European ecosystem","carbon budget; climate change; ecosystem dynamics; terrestrial ecosystem; Europe",,,,,,"Barnola, J.M., Raynaud, D., Korotkevitch, Y.S., Lorius, C., Vostok ice core provides 160 000 years record of atmospheric CO2 (1987) Nature, 329, pp. 408-414; Bartlett, S.B., Whiting, G.J., Hartman, J.M., Use of vegetation indices to estimate intercepted solar radiation and net carbon dioxide exchange of a grass canopy (1990) Remote Sens. Environ., 30, pp. 115-128; Bazzaz, F.A., Fajer, E.D., Plant life in a CO2-rich world (1992) Sci. Am., 266, pp. 68-74; Bazzaz, F.A., The effects of increasing atmospheric CO2 on the earth's vegetation (1994) Proc. First GCTE Sci. Conf.: Global Change and Terrestrial Ecosystem, , Woods Hole, MA, USA; Box, E.O., Estimating the seasonal carbon source-sink geography of a nature, steady-state terrestrial biosphere (1988) J. Appl. Meteorol., 27, pp. 109-1124; Ceulemans, R., Mousseau, M., Effects of elevated atmospheric CO2 on woody plants (1994) New Phytol., 127, pp. 425-446; Major climatic changes of last 18 000 years: Observations and model simulations (1988) Science, 241, pp. 1043-1052. , COHMAP Project Members; Dai, A., Fung, I.Y., Can climate variability contribute to the 'missing' CO2 sink? (1993) Global Biogeochem. Cycle, 7, pp. 599-609; Denton, G.H., Hughes, T.J., (1981) The Last Great Ice Sheets., , Wiley, New York. 484 pp; Emanual, W.R., Shugart, H.H., Stevenson, M.P., Climatic change and the broad-scale distribution of terrestrial ecosystem complexes (1985) Climatic Change, 7, pp. 29-43; Esser, G., Sensitivity of global carbon pools and fluxes to human and potential climatic impacts (1987) Tellus, 39, pp. 245-260; Esser, G., Osnabrück Biosphere Model: S